1.name: Core Safety Surface
1.description: String, malloc, errno — highest-impact, lowest-complexity families that form the foundation for safe memory operations.
1.rationale: These families are called on virtually every code path and have the highest ROI for native implementation.

2.name: Numeric & stdlib Foundation
2.description: Math, stdlib, wchar — medium-complexity families needed for numeric computing and wide-string support.
2.rationale: Widely used in scientific and text-processing workloads; currently many symbols are native.

3.name: Threading & Synchronization
3.description: Pthread family — high-complexity but critical for multi-threaded applications.
3.rationale: Thread safety is a key differentiator; migrating from GlibcCallThrough to native eliminates host-libc dependency for concurrency.

4.name: I/O & Networking
4.description: stdio, socket, unistd, poll, io, mmap — I/O-heavy families that require syscall expertise.
4.rationale: I/O families have high symbol count and complex state; wave 4 tackles them after safety and threading foundations are solid.

5.name: System Integration & Remaining
5.description: All remaining families: process, signal, time, dirent, dlfcn, resolv, inet, locale, iconv, grp, pwd, termios, resource, startup.
5.rationale: Lower-frequency families needed for full glibc replacement; completed last to minimize risk to core functionality.

wave_acceptance_checklist.description: All wave symbols must be natively implemented (not host-delegated)
Every symbol must have at least 1 conformance fixture case
Each symbol must have regression tests in the harness
Both strict and hardened modes tested for each symbol
Structured JSONL evidence for each symbol's validation outcome
Family-level fuzz target exercises the symbol (waves 1-3)
